segments.text: Robert Smith's area, so forth and so on.
But anyway, the capital fund drive is in part a response to the treatment that we're being accorded.

It's unfortunate that some years back, back when I suppose it was sort of the golden era of higher education growth in the state when Connolly was governor, but we created a lot of schools that are underutilized, but once created,
They cannot be dismantled.
Would you comment in that connection on the traditional Texas A&M versus University of Texas conflict over funding and competition generally?
That's an interesting thing.
Historically, apparently, there was this conflict, and each college, each university sought to have its own graduates in the legislature and all of that.
But there was ushered in, in the last seven or eight years, much more of a cooperative effort.
For example, it's not a case of collusion, but it is a fact that UT and A&M consulted with each other over admission standards.
so as not to end up being played one against the other.
They collaborated along with Houston, I guess, in the establishment of – I've forgotten exactly what they're called.
They're like outreach centers.
There's one in San Antonio.
Yeah, I know which one.
That's certainly a collaborative effort.
In your college, you know that Fallon instituted the practice of the executive committees of the two colleges meeting either once a year or twice a year, one time there and one time here.
An exchange of faculty has been utilized.
What about collaboration at the legislative level?
I can't really speak to that, but I think that there
I sense that, yeah.
I think there's been a big change in that relationship, but I don't really know, you know.
Yeah, well, you remember the big effort to, what was it called, when things got really tight, we got this sort of state-level NSF to provide funding, and that was a collaborative effort.
Yeah, that's right.
The creation of that.
I think that's been one of the most significant changes in the last, whatever.

Well, when we got over our guilt complex, or our inferiority, not guilt, but inferiority complex, about being second to them or whatever, and everybody started talking about the two flagship institutions.
That's right.
That is a different perception.
That's a good point, rather than the University of Texas.
And you need to look at the...
At the charts on our outside funding for research, we rank seventh.
We rank ahead of UT.
Of course, there's a little cheating going on.
And all that money going to ag from the experiment station stuff and engineering experiment, especially ag, kind of inflates the figures a bit.
But it's still significant.
That's right.
And it is much more.
We continue, because image lags behind performance by something like a decade or two, we continue, I suppose, not to be as well recognized nationally as we're going to be.
But I recall having a conversation with a New York Times reporter when Shelley Glashow was on campus.
and I ended up being the spokesperson because everybody else was out of town except the Chancellor and me, and it was Anson at the time.
Shelly was on campus and the guy in helicopters came in from Houston with the press, you know, and we were interviewed outside the Koch building.
And the question was asked, you know, what's going on here?
Almost incredulous, this guy from the New York Times
I was saying, what's happening down there?

And I said, well, you know, in the beginning there was the Ivy League, and they were the top institutions in the country, and then gradually great schools developed in the Midwest, like the University of Chicago, Michigan, Ohio State, Wisconsin, and then on
over to the West Coast and a California assistant at Stanford.
And now it's the South's turn.
We can be as good as anybody.
Our time has arrived.
That's good.
That's a good .
And the guy said, hmm, well, you know, you got a point there.
That's good.
That was at a time, of course, when oil was still poor.
Yes, that does make a difference, boy.
But, you know, here we are now in the Sun Belt, and an area that used to be known as the industrial heart of America is called the Rust Belt.
That's right.
Times have changed.
They sure have.
Well, what do you, if you had to reflect on your days at Texas A&M, is there any sort of...
centrality or theme or general evaluation you would give that time?
I think we became a very different institution.
This is not to say that the school of yesteryear was not an outstanding one in its way, but I think that General Rudder didn't think that dog was going to hunt.
much longer.
Here we were sitting on one of the biggest, certainly maybe the biggest state campus in the country, and maybe the biggest campus in the country, 5,200 acres and a handful of students.
And he was astute enough to see that things had to change.
It was interesting, you know his strategy, well I guess this has been written
But he adopted a strategy which economists call the leading edge concept.
He picked two departments to make superstars out of.
One was economics and the other was chemistry.
He brought in Greenhut and what's his name?
Cotton?
Not Cotton.
The guy he brought in brought Cotton in.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
He was department head for a long time.
thought that the institution should be as large as it became.
And had I been the benevolent king of this place, it would have stopped at 25,000.
Yeah, that's a number I remember jingling around.
You get all the advantages of scale, and beyond that you just get trouble.
I think we really did have growing pains because we grew so fast.
We were frequently short of classroom space.
We pumped a lot of money into research.
If you look at the numbers, a major part of the construction on this campus can be attributed to research.
One of the things that
did, I think, contribute to the continuance of this phenomenon of the Aggie spirit, which in itself I can't really understand.
I can't really understand how it is still so strong, but it is.
I agree.
I wonder how long that's going to last.
I wonder, too.
It's obviously not what it was when the Corps was so dominant.
But anyway, what I started to say was one of the things that
probably helped keep this such a friendly campus was the fact that we never really did build massive lecture halls.
Classes are still quite small, relatively speaking, for an institution of this size.
This size, you're right.
That's one point.
And another point that Glenn Dowling can give you very good data on is compared to, I'd say, almost any, if not all, other major institutions in the country,
We have more real faculty, and that's not the right word, tenured or tenure-track faculty teaching at the undergraduate level.
We take a place, I was reading about Southern Illinois, the provost was quoted a few years ago as saying, God, none of our courses at the undergraduate level are taught by professors.
But that's not true here.
No, not at all.
So I think that's been a very positive thing that has, I think, enriched the students' experience here.
Do you think the mothers clubs and the former students have been an enriching process?
I think yes.
I think yes.
I think this place has done a remarkable job of indoctrination.
of both students and parents.
We have one of the best, and people tell us this that have gone to other schools, that we have the best orientation program of any.
Incidentally, I still hear people say how much they enjoyed your program.
I have a story to tell you about that later.
But I think it's really from the
the silver taps, the muster.
Yeah, muster.
Fish camp, I think, is doing a good job now in picking up some of that preservation of the spirit and its non-core, and that's helped a lot.
I think this place, and another thing that is a phenomenon probably not duplicated in many institutions is this
is all of the student organizations under the MSC.
MSC, yeah.
That gives them a leadership and a...
Political forum, great issues, SCONA, all that stuff.

Somehow or other, you know, I've always felt, and I'm not trying to put words in your mouth, that students who come out of A&M, in a way, have come out of the real world more so than students who come out of a lot of institutions, and that has been one of the great strengths of the...
of the graduate in the job market.
I think so.
A lot of them have learned a lot about leadership.
That's right.
And, of course, there's this Aggie network out there that's not just good old boys now, but good old girls.
Serious stuff.
Serious stuff.
Aggies have a reputation for being hardworking youngsters.
You know, Hyde was involved.
back in the earlier years with the Center for Management Training, Executive Development.
Yes, yeah, sure.
And businessmen would come to these programs, men, mostly men, sometimes a few women, but businesspersons who had been on other campuses.
They couldn't believe what they were seeing.
They couldn't believe the friendliness of the students.
They couldn't believe how clean the campus was.
It was an eye-opener for a lot of them.
I guess that program's still going well, isn't it?
I know it was a few years ago.
And who's the new head of, he was in that, gosh.
Duke Hobbs heads it now.
Who was in that with you when you were running that program?
Billy Joe Adams.
And someone else, let's see, who's now a head of a department in business, just accepted the headship about a year ago, and who I thought was ready to hang it all up.
Oh, Don Elrigal was one that came back after being a department head before.
I'm surprised he agreed to do it again.
Do it again, I know.
I think what has happened with Don is he's made a reputation for himself.
He's got some highly successful textbooks.
I see him out at the baseball games all the time.
You can't keep your nose to the grindstone and spend hours at the .
Don never really was too much involved in the executive development program, but he was once a chancellor.
Yeah, I know.
Yeah.
He's a very talented guy.
Well, let's see.
Let's talk very quickly, sort of a summary statement.
Where do we go from here, do you think?
What do you see happening in the major thrust or directions of the university?
I hope we can continue to preserve this Aggie spirit.
I think it gets increasingly difficult with the size that we've achieved.
I see the institution.
continuing to get better.
I don't see really dramatic changes of the magnitude that you and I have experienced, though.
Given the size, there's an awful lot of inertia connected with size.
Until the financing situation changes, we don't have a lot of room to be innovative.
I would like to see us have someday a full-blown fine arts program.
But this is going to be something that doesn't happen overnight.
Dogs knocking on the door.
Yeah, mine does too.
You have to get up and go.
Yeah, you got left out of the scene, huh?
Okay, now, Max, we're writing.
Sit down.
Sit, sit, sit, sit, sit.
You're supposed to say when I say sit.
And you said a moment ago that probably the image of the A&M will be better because images follow by a decade.
Yeah, or at least, yeah.
Well, is there anything else you would like to add to this?
No.
And I may call you along the way.
Yeah, feel free to do so.
I really don't quite get what I'm doing.
I'm just going to do something.
Well, I'll close it off.
